#: ../../api/memory.md:18
msgid "`axiom.retrieval.fusion`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion:1 of
msgid "Rank fusion for hybrid search."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion:3 of
msgid ""
"Algorithm adapted from Hindsight (MIT, ``engine/search/fusion.py``), kept"
" dependency-free and deterministic. We fuse *ranked lists of document "
"ids* (one per retrieval arm — semantic, lexical, …) into a single ranking"
" using Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion:8 of
msgid ""
"RRF is rank-based, not score-based, on purpose: each arm produces scores "
"on its own incomparable scale (cosine distance vs BM25), so combining raw"
" scores would let one arm's scale dominate. RRF only looks at *where* a "
"document ranks within each arm, which makes the arms commensurable."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.cap_per_source:1 of
msgid "Truncate a single arm's ranked ids to its top ``cap``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.cap_per_source:3 of
msgid ""
"Applied per arm *before* fusion so one over-expanding backend cannot "
"crowd out the others. ``cap <= 0`` disables the cap. The caller is "
"responsible for ordering ``ranked_ids`` best-first; this only slices."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.reciprocal_rank_fusion:1 of
msgid "Merge several ranked id lists into one via Reciprocal Rank Fusion."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.reciprocal_rank_fusion:3 of
msgid ""
"RRF formula: ``score(d) = sum over arms of 1 / (k + rank(d))`` where "
"``rank`` is 1-based within each arm. A document absent from an arm "
"contributes nothing for that arm."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.reciprocal_rank_fusion:7 of
msgid "One list of document ids per arm, each ordered best-first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.reciprocal_rank_fusion:8 of
msgid ""
"RRF damping constant (default 60). Larger ``k`` flattens the contribution"
" of top ranks, smaller ``k`` sharpens it."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.fusion.reciprocal_rank_fusion:11 of
msgid ""
"``(doc_id, rrf_score)`` pairs sorted by score descending. Ties are broken"
" deterministically by first appearance order across the input lists, so "
"the result is stable for identical inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:25
msgid "`axiom.retrieval.lexical`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical:1 of
msgid "Lexical (BM25) retrieval arm."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical:3 of
msgid ""
"The semantic arm (sentence-transformer embeddings) is great at meaning "
"but can miss an *exact* token the player typed — a proper noun "
"(\"Kael\"), an item name, a coined word — because such tokens carry "
"little distributed meaning. BM25 is the classic lexical complement: it "
"rewards rare exact-term overlap. We fuse the two arms with Reciprocal "
"Rank Fusion (see ``fusion.py``)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical:9 of
msgid ""
"Graceful degradation: if ``rank_bm25`` is unavailable the lexical arm is "
"simply absent and search falls back to the semantic arm alone (no crash),"
" mirroring the ``VectorMemory._disabled`` philosophy for the embedding "
"runtime."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical:13 of
msgid ""
"Algorithm reference: Hindsight (MIT) runs BM25 in Postgres "
"(``tsvector``); that SQL is not portable, so we reimplement the *idea* "
"with the pure-Python ``rank_bm25`` library over the in-memory corpus of a"
" save's chunks."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.is_available:1 of
msgid "True when the BM25 backend can be used."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.tokenize:1 of
msgid "Deterministic, Unicode-aware word tokenizer (lowercased)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.tokenize:3 of
msgid ""
"Splits on anything that is not a word character, so punctuation and "
"underscores act as separators. Keeps accented letters and non-Latin "
"scripts (the game ships 10 languages), so a name like ``\"Kaël\"`` stays "
"one token."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.build_bm25:1 of
msgid "Build a BM25 index over ``corpus_texts`` (or ``None`` if unavailable)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.build_bm25:3 of
msgid ""
"Split out from :func:`rank_by_bm25` so callers can *cache* the index when"
" the corpus is unchanged (building it tokenises the whole corpus and "
"computes IDF — the expensive part), then score many queries against it "
"cheaply."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_with_bm25:1 of
msgid "Rank ``corpus_ids`` against a pre-built ``bm25`` index, best first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_with_bm25:3 of
msgid ""
"``corpus_ids`` must be aligned 1:1 with the texts the index was built "
"from. Returns an empty list when the index is ``None`` or the query has "
"no usable tokens; drops zero-score docs (no lexical signal). Ties keep "
"input order."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:1 of
msgid "Rank ``corpus_ids`` by BM25 relevance to ``query_text``, best first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:3 of
msgid ""
"Convenience wrapper that builds a one-shot index then scores. Hot paths "
"that reuse a stable corpus should cache :func:`build_bm25` and call "
":func:`rank_with_bm25` instead."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:7 of
msgid "The raw query string."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:8 of
msgid "Stable ids, aligned 1:1 with ``corpus_texts``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:9 of
msgid "The chunk texts to score against the query."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.lexical.rank_by_bm25:11 of
msgid ""
"``corpus_ids`` reordered by descending BM25 score, dropping documents "
"whose score is zero (no query-term overlap → no lexical signal). Returns "
"an empty list when BM25 is unavailable or the query has no usable tokens."
" Ties keep the input order (deterministic)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:32
msgid "`axiom.retrieval.reranker`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:1 of
msgid "Optional cross-encoder reranking."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:3 of
msgid ""
"The retrieval arms (semantic embeddings + BM25) score a document "
"*independently* of the query's other terms. A **cross-encoder** instead "
"reads the (query, document) pair *jointly* and judges their relevance "
"directly — the most accurate ranking signal available, used as the final "
"re-sort after fusion."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:8 of
msgid "It is **OFF by default** and **degrades to a no-op** when unavailable:"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:10 of
msgid ""
"needs a torch model (~90 MB, ``cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2``), "
"the same native runtime that fails on Windows without VC++ (TICKET-070);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:12 of
msgid ""
"the heavy import / model load is lazy and guarded, so a missing or broken"
" runtime simply means \"no reranking\", never a crash."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker:15 of
msgid ""
"Algorithm reference: Hindsight (MIT, ``engine/search/reranking.py``). "
"Local sentence-transformers cross-encoders return logits → squashed to "
"[0, 1] with a sigmoid; already-calibrated [0, 1] scores are passed "
"through."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker.CrossEncoderReranker:1 of
msgid "Lazy wrapper around a sentence-transformers ``CrossEncoder``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker.CrossEncoderReranker:3 of
msgid "HuggingFace cross-encoder id (default ms-marco MiniLM)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker.CrossEncoderReranker:4 of
msgid ""
"Pre-built model with a ``predict(pairs)`` method. Injecting one bypasses "
"loading entirely — used by tests to stay deterministic and offline."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker.CrossEncoderReranker.rerank:1 of
msgid "Score each document's relevance to the query, in [0, 1]."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.retrieval.reranker.CrossEncoderReranker.rerank:3 of
msgid ""
"Returns scores aligned 1:1 with ``documents``, or ``None`` when the "
"reranker is unavailable / fails (the caller then keeps the fused order)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:39
msgid "`axiom.facts`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts:1 of
msgid "Structured-fact storage for \"living\" memory mode."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts:3 of
msgid ""
"In living mode the engine distils each turn's narrative into atomic "
"**facts** (a who/what/when/where/why model adapted from Hindsight) and "
"stores them here, tagged with the ``turn_id`` that produced them. The "
"turn tag makes rollback trivial — rewinding to turn N simply drops every "
"fact from a later turn — and keeps the facts in lockstep with the event "
"log they were derived from."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts:9 of
msgid ""
"This module is the *deterministic* storage layer: no LLM, no network. The"
" LLM extraction that produces the facts lives in ``axiom.factextract``; "
"the background job that calls it lives in the app's worker layer. Facts "
"live in the same SQLite database as ``Event_Log`` / ``State_Cache`` "
"(keyed by ``save_id`` + ``turn_id``)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.Fact:1 of
msgid "One atomic fact extracted from the narrative."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.Fact:3 of
msgid ""
"``statement`` is the canonical one-sentence form used for "
"recall/embedding; the who/what/when/where/why fields are the structured "
"decomposition."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.insert_facts:1 of
msgid "Persist a turn's extracted facts. Returns the new ``fact_id`` values."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.insert_facts:3 of
msgid ""
"Empty statements are skipped (an extractor that found nothing is normal "
"and must not write blank rows). Idempotency is the caller's concern: re-"
"extracting a turn should first ``rollback_facts`` to that turn."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.insert_facts:7 of
msgid ""
"Side effect: each ``Fact`` that is actually inserted has its ``fact_id`` "
"and ``turn_id`` set in place, so the caller can use the objects directly "
"without re-aligning a separate id list (skipped/blank facts keep "
"``fact_id=None``)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.get_facts:1 of
msgid "Fetch a save's facts, most recent first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.get_facts:3 of
msgid ""
"Only facts from turns ``<= max_turn_id`` (honours the history window / "
"rewind horizon). ``None`` = no upper bound."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.get_facts:5 of
msgid ""
"Keep only facts whose ``entities`` list contains this name (case-"
"insensitive exact match). ``None`` = no filter."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.get_facts:7 axiom.mental_models.get_mental_models:7
#: axiom.observations.get_observations:7 of
msgid "Cap the number of rows returned."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.count_facts:1 of
msgid "Number of stored facts for a save (cheap COUNT)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.rollback_facts:1 of
msgid ""
"Delete a save's facts from turns after ``target_turn_id``. Returns the "
"count."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.facts.rollback_facts:3 of
msgid ""
"Standalone helper (opens its own connection). The in-session rewind path "
"deletes facts inside ``CheckpointManager.rewind``'s own transaction "
"instead, so events and facts roll back atomically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:46
msgid "`axiom.factextract`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:1 of
msgid "LLM fact extraction for living memory mode."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:3 of
msgid ""
"Turns a slice of narrative prose into a list of atomic, structured "
":class:`~axiom.facts.Fact` objects via an "
":class:`~axiom.backends.base.LLMBackend`. The who/what/when/where/why "
"schema and the \"atomic, verifiable, no speculation\" discipline are "
"adapted from Hindsight's ``retain/fact_extraction.py`` prompt, "
"reimplemented for our backend (causal links deliberately left out — see "
"Phase 2 DOC). Causal relations / consolidation come later."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:10 of
msgid "Design rules:"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:12 axiom.reflect:11 of
msgid ""
"**Background only**: callers run this off the turn loop; it must never "
"block play."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:13 of
msgid ""
"**Graceful**: any failure (LLM down, bad JSON, cancellation) yields "
"``[]`` — the game keeps running, the turn simply produced no facts."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract:15 of
msgid ""
"**No persistence here**: returns ``Fact`` objects; the worker stores them"
" via ``axiom.facts.insert_facts`` (tagged with the turn id)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.factextract.extract_facts:1 of
msgid "Extract structured facts from ``narrative_text`` using ``llm``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.consolidate:9 axiom.factextract.extract_facts:3 of
msgid ""
"Returns ``[]`` for empty input or on any backend/parse failure (never "
"raises), so a living-mode background job can call it fire-and-forget."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:53
msgid "`axiom.observations`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:1 of
msgid "Consolidated-belief storage for \"living\" memory mode (Phase 3)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:3 of
msgid ""
"Where :mod:`axiom.facts` stores the atomic, immutable facts extracted "
"each turn, this module stores **observations** — synthetic *beliefs* that"
" evolve as facts accumulate (a Hindsight-inspired idea: an NPC remembers "
"a betrayal hundreds of turns later and revises its opinion). A belief "
"carries:"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:8 of
msgid "``statement`` — the canonical belief, one sentence;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:9 of
msgid "``subject``   — the entity it is about / who holds it (\"\" = the world);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:10 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid "``sources``   — the supporting facts as ``[{\"fact_id\", \"turn_id\"}]``;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:11 of
msgid "``proof_count`` — cached ``len(sources)``;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:12 of
msgid "``history``   — JSON trail of CREATE/UPDATE/DELETE changes."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:14 of
msgid ""
"This is the *deterministic* storage + rollback layer (no LLM, no "
"network). The LLM consolidation that decides CREATE/UPDATE/DELETE lives "
"in ``axiom.consolidate``; the background job that calls it lives in the "
"app layer."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations:18 of
msgid ""
"**Rollback (the hard part, solved).** Beliefs derive from several turns, "
"so a plain ``turn_id`` column is not enough. The ``sources`` turn ids are"
" the rollback key: rewinding to turn N drops every belief *created* after"
" N and, for the survivors, keeps only the sources at turns ``<= N``, "
"recomputing ``proof_count`` and flagging ``stale`` so the next "
"consolidation pass re-examines them. Beliefs thus roll back atomically "
"with the facts/events they were built from."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:1 of
msgid "Classify a belief's trend from the turn ids of its supporting sources."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:3 of
msgid "Returns one of the ``TREND_*`` constants:"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:5 of
msgid "``NEW``           — every source falls in the recent window;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:6 of
msgid "``STRENGTHENING`` — denser recent evidence than older (ratio > 1.5);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:7 of
msgid "``WEAKENING``     — sparser recent evidence than older (ratio < 0.5);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:8 of
msgid "``STALE``         — no source in the recent window (may be outdated);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:9 of
msgid ""
"``STABLE``        — steady, or trend unknown (no sources / no current "
"turn)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.compute_trend:11 of
msgid ""
"Deterministic and side-effect free. ``now_turn`` is the current turn (the"
" rewind horizon during replay), so the trend is always read at the right "
"\"now\"."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.Observation:1 of
msgid "One consolidated belief."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.Observation:3 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"``sources`` is a list of ``{\"fact_id\": int, \"turn_id\": int}`` dicts —"
" the facts backing the belief and the turns they came from (the rollback "
"key)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.Observation.trend:1 of
msgid "This belief's trend at ``now_turn`` (see :func:`compute_trend`)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.insert_observation:1 of
msgid "Persist a single new belief. Returns its ``observation_id`` (or ``None``)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.insert_observation:3 of
msgid ""
"Blank statements are skipped (an empty belief is never written). "
"``proof_count`` is derived from ``sources`` so it can never disagree with"
" them."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.get_observations:1 of
msgid "Fetch a save's beliefs, most recently updated first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.get_observations:3 of
msgid ""
"Only beliefs created at turns ``<= max_turn_id`` (honours the history "
"window / rewind horizon). ``None`` = no bound."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.get_observations:5 of
msgid ""
"Keep only beliefs whose ``subject`` matches (case-insensitive). ``None`` "
"= no filter; ``\"\"`` keeps the world-level beliefs."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.count_observations:1 of
msgid "Number of stored beliefs for a save (cheap COUNT)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:1 of
msgid "Roll a save's beliefs back to their state at ``target_turn_id``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:3 of
msgid ""
"Operates on an already-open connection so ``CheckpointManager.rewind`` "
"can run it inside the same transaction as the Event_Log / Facts deletes "
"(atomic)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:6
#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:6 of
msgid "Rule (see module docstring):"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:7 of
msgid "belief ``created_turn_id > target`` → it did not exist yet → DELETE;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:8 of
msgid ""
"else keep its sources at turns ``<= target``; if any were dropped (an "
"UPDATE absorbed a now-rewound fact) recompute ``proof_count``, clamp "
"``updated_turn_id`` to ``<= target`` and flag ``stale`` for the next "
"consolidation pass."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:12
#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations:13 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid "Returns ``{\"deleted\": n, \"updated\": m}``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.apply_consolidation:1 of
msgid "Apply consolidator actions (CREATE/UPDATE/DELETE) to the beliefs store."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.apply_consolidation:3 of
msgid ""
"Deterministic: it just executes the decisions the LLM already made (the "
"LLM call lives in ``axiom.consolidate``). ``fact_turn_map`` maps each "
"cited ``fact_id`` to its ``turn_id`` so new sources carry the turn (the "
"rollback key). Unknown belief ids / empty statements are skipped. Returns"
" counts."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.apply_consolidation:8 of
msgid ""
"The turn this consolidation pass runs at — stamped as the "
"``updated_turn_id`` (and ``created_turn_id`` for new beliefs)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations_standalone:1 of
msgid "Standalone variant of :func:`rollback_observations` (opens its own conn)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.observations.rollback_observations_standalone:3 of
msgid ""
"The in-session rewind path uses the connection-based variant so events, "
"facts and beliefs roll back in one transaction; this helper is for tests "
"and out-of-band cleanup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:60
msgid "`axiom.consolidate`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:1 of
msgid "LLM belief consolidation for living memory mode (Phase 3)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:3 of
msgid ""
"Turns a batch of freshly-extracted :class:`~axiom.facts.Fact` objects, "
"together with the beliefs already held, into a list of **consolidation "
"actions** (CREATE / UPDATE / DELETE "
":class:`~axiom.observations.Observation`). The decision rules — prefer "
"UPDATE over duplicate CREATE, one facet per belief, be conservative about"
" DELETE, never do arithmetic, preserve what changed — are adapted from "
"Hindsight's ``consolidation/prompts.py``, reimplemented on our "
":class:`~axiom.backends.base.LLMBackend`."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:11 of
msgid "Design rules (same discipline as ``axiom.factextract``):"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:13 of
msgid ""
"**Background only**: callers run this off the turn loop; it must never "
"block."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:14 of
msgid ""
"**Graceful**: any failure (LLM down, bad JSON) yields ``[]`` — no belief "
"changes this pass, the game keeps running."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate:16 of
msgid ""
"**No persistence here**: returns action objects; the deterministic "
"application to the DB lives in "
"``axiom.observations.apply_consolidation``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.ConsolidationAction:1 of
msgid "One belief change proposed by the consolidator LLM."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.consolidate:1 of
msgid "Ask ``llm`` how the beliefs should change given ``new_facts``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.consolidate:3 of
msgid "The universe-wide default mission (what this world remembers)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.consolidate:4 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Per-character memory styles ``{entity_name: mission}`` (B-3) — only those"
" whose character appears in this batch are shown."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.consolidate.consolidate:6 of
msgid ""
"Cap on existing beliefs shown to the LLM (TICKET-077); scoped to the "
"batch's characters + most recent. ``<= 0`` disables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:67
msgid "`axiom.missions`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:1 of
msgid "Per-character belief missions (Phase 4, B-3)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:3 of
msgid ""
"A *belief mission* is a memory style for the consolidator: what a "
"character tends to remember and dwell on (a rancorous NPC remembers "
"betrayals, a merchant remembers transactions, a loyal guard remembers "
"favours). It biases which beliefs :mod:`axiom.consolidate` forms about "
"each subject, so NPCs \"remember differently\" according to their nature."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:9 of
msgid ""
"Stored in ``Universe_Meta`` (no schema change; it round-trips losslessly "
"through the Universe-as-Code ``[extra]`` mechanism, is copied into saves,"
" and is packaged):"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:13 of
msgid "``belief_mission``  — the universe-wide default mission (one string);"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:14 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"``belief_missions`` — JSON ``{entity_name: mission}`` per-character "
"overrides."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions:16 of
msgid ""
"Keyed by entity *name* because a belief's ``subject`` is a name and "
"authoring \"Name: mission\" is natural. Reading degrades gracefully "
"(missing/blank/malformed → sensible empties) so the consolidator always "
"has something usable."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.get_universe_mission:1 of
msgid "The universe-wide default belief mission (\"\" when unset)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.get_belief_missions_from_value:1 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid "Parse a ``belief_missions`` JSON value into ``{entity_name: mission}``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.get_belief_missions_from_value:3 of
msgid ""
"Tolerates blank/malformed JSON or non-string values — anything unusable "
"is dropped rather than raised. Used when the meta value is already in "
"hand (e.g. the Studio's loaded meta dict)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.get_belief_missions:1 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid "Per-character missions as ``{entity_name: mission}`` read from the DB."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.parse_missions_text:1 of
#, python-brace-format
msgid "Parse a 'Name: mission' per-line block into ``{name: mission}``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.parse_missions_text:3 of
msgid ""
"The GUI Metadata field stores missions this way (one entity per line). "
"Lines without a colon, or with an empty name/mission, are skipped. The "
"first colon splits — a mission may itself contain colons."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.missions.missions_to_text:1 of
msgid "Inverse of :func:`parse_missions_text` for displaying in the GUI field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:74
msgid "`axiom.mental_models`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:1 of
msgid "Mental-model storage for \"living\" memory mode (Hindsight §7.8)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:3 of
msgid ""
"A **mental model** is a curated, synthetic profile — one per subject (a "
"character, or ``\"\"`` for the world) — that sits *above* the beliefs in "
"the recall hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:6 of
msgid ""
"mental model  →  beliefs (observations)  →  facts  →  raw narrative "
"chunks (most synthetic)                                       (most raw)"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:9 of
msgid ""
"Where a belief is one durable statement, a mental model is a short "
"paragraph that distils *all* of a subject's beliefs into \"who this is "
"now\": their relationships, goals, grudges and how they have changed. The"
" narrator reads it first, so a long campaign's accumulated memory lands "
"as a coherent character note rather than a pile of disjointed facts."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:15 of
msgid ""
"Idea adapted from Hindsight (MIT, ``reflect/``): their reflect agent "
"maintains curated *mental models* above the raw memories. We keep the "
"**principle of a synthetic top layer** but drop the heavy tool-calling "
"agent — for a single-player game one regenerated paragraph per subject is"
" enough."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:20 of
msgid ""
"This module is the *deterministic* storage + rollback layer (no LLM, no "
"network). The LLM that writes the summary lives in :mod:`axiom.reflect`; "
"the background job that calls it lives in the app's worker layer."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models:24 of
msgid ""
"**Rollback.** A mental model is fully reconstructible from the beliefs it"
" was built from (which themselves roll back correctly), so rewinding to "
"turn N only has to: drop every model *created* after N, and flag the "
"survivors ``stale`` (clamping ``updated_turn_id``) so the next refresh "
"regenerates them from the rewound beliefs. There is at most one model per"
" ``(save_id, subject)`` — refresh is an UPSERT."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.MentalModel:1 of
msgid "One curated profile for a subject (a character, or \"\" for the world)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.MentalModel:3 of
msgid ""
"``sources`` is a list of the ``observation_id`` values the summary was "
"built from (kept for traceability / future link expansion; the rollback "
"key is the turn ids, which the beliefs themselves carry)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.upsert_mental_model:1 of
msgid ""
"Create or refresh the mental model for ``subject``. Returns its "
"``model_id``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.upsert_mental_model:3 of
msgid ""
"There is at most one model per ``(save_id, subject)``: an existing one is"
" updated in place (``created_turn_id`` preserved), otherwise a new one is"
" inserted. Blank summaries are skipped (never overwrite a profile with "
"nothing)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.get_mental_models:1 of
msgid "Fetch a save's mental models, most recently updated first."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.get_mental_models:3 of
msgid ""
"Only models created at turns ``<= max_turn_id`` (honours the rewind "
"horizon). ``None`` = no bound."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.get_mental_models:5 of
msgid ""
"Keep only the model for this subject (case-insensitive). ``\"\"`` keeps "
"the world-level model."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.count_mental_models:1 of
msgid "Number of stored mental models for a save (cheap COUNT)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.stale_subjects:1 of
msgid "Subjects whose model is flagged ``stale`` (oldest update first)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.stale_subjects:3 of
msgid ""
"A rewind flags survivors stale; this lets the refresh job find and "
"regenerate them even when their beliefs do not change again. Capped so a "
"long backlog never floods one consolidation pass."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:1 of
msgid "Roll a save's mental models back to their state at ``target_turn_id``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:3 of
msgid ""
"Operates on an already-open connection so ``CheckpointManager.rewind`` "
"can run it inside the same transaction as the Event_Log / Facts / "
"Observations deletes."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:7 of
msgid "model ``created_turn_id > target`` → did not exist yet → DELETE;"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models:8 of
msgid ""
"else, if it was last refreshed after the target, clamp "
"``updated_turn_id`` to ``target`` and flag ``stale`` so the next refresh "
"regenerates it from the rewound beliefs (the old summary stays as a "
"graceful fallback meanwhile)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.mental_models.rollback_mental_models_standalone:1 of
msgid "Standalone variant of :func:`rollback_mental_models` (opens its own conn)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../api/memory.md:81
msgid "`axiom.reflect`"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect:1 of
msgid "LLM generation of mental models for living memory mode (Hindsight §7.8)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect:3 of
msgid ""
"Turns the beliefs held about one subject (a character, or the world) into"
" a short **mental model**: a 2-4 sentence profile of who that subject is "
"*now*. The decision discipline — base it only on the beliefs, no "
"invention, no arithmetic, capture change and relationships — is adapted "
"from Hindsight's ``reflect/`` prompts, reimplemented on our "
":class:`~axiom.backends.base.LLMBackend`."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect:9 of
msgid ""
"Design rules (same as :mod:`axiom.factextract` / "
":mod:`axiom.consolidate`):"
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect:12 of
msgid ""
"**Graceful**: any failure (LLM down, empty answer) yields ``\"\"`` — the "
"profile is simply not refreshed this pass, the game keeps running."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect:14 of
msgid ""
"**No persistence here**: returns the summary string; the deterministic "
"UPSERT lives in :func:`axiom.mental_models.upsert_mental_model`."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect.affected_subjects:1 of
msgid ""
"Subjects whose beliefs changed in a consolidation batch (order-"
"preserving)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect.affected_subjects:3 of
msgid ""
"Reads the ``subject`` of each create/update action (delete actions drop a"
" belief and don't name a subject worth re-modelling here). De-duplicated "
"case-insensitively, keeping first-seen spelling. World beliefs "
"(``subject=\"\"``) are included (the world model)."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect.reflect:1 of
msgid "Write a mental-model summary for ``subject`` from its ``beliefs``."
msgstr ""

#: axiom.reflect.reflect:3 of
msgid ""
"Returns ``\"\"`` when there are too few beliefs to be worth modelling, on"
" empty input, or on any backend failure (never raises) — so a living-mode"
" background job can call it fire-and-forget."
msgstr ""

